column8: [Model Launch] Qwen 3 Is Now on Kaggle!
column10:
Kaggle







Hi Candace Grant,

We're excited to share that Qwen 3, the long awaited next generation ofLLMs in the Qwen series, is now live! This collection includes a variety ofmodels built to provide strong performance and flexibility for a wide rangeof AI tasks. With different model sizes and advanced reasoningcapabilities, Qwen 3 is suitable for diverse applications.

These models offer Apache 2.0 open licensing for easy customization andfine-tuning. They also excel in human-aligned interactions, making themideal for creative writing, multi-turn conversations, role-play andinstruction following.





Access Qwen 3



Key Features:


Varied Model Sizes: The suite includes six instruct models, base versions,quantized variants, and two sparse mixture of expert (MoE) models(Qwen3-235B-A22B and Qwen3-30B-A3B).
Dual-mode performance: Models switch between ‚Äúthinking‚Äù mode (for logicalreasoning, coding, and math) and ‚Äúnon-thinking‚Äù mode (for fast, casualdialogue), enabling versatile applications.
Advanced Agent Capabilities: Integrates smoothly with tools and excels inagent-based environments, supporting complex, autonomous workflow.
Multilingual Fluency: Supports 100+ languages dialects, making it ideal forglobal applications like translation and multilingual chatbots.


We're excited to see how the Kaggle community will explore and apply thesemodels to their own projects and research.

Brenda Flynn
Kaggle Partnerships Lead



Kaggle, Inc 1600 Amphitheatre Pkwy Mountain View, CA 94043

This email was sent to aicoaching2025@gmail.com because you indicated thatyou'd like to receive news and updates about Kaggle. If you don't want toreceive these emails in the future, please unsubscribe here. You can alsochange your preferences on your account's profile page by logging in atkaggle.com.

Hey Candace,

Hope you‚Äôre well.

It‚Äôs been a bit of a stressful day as we‚Äôve been launching our
new product The $1k Challenge (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/n4u4z20wxvavhxn3vx8a6h6pq0kggalhgvoew/n2h4q6lrfquvklv0k7a0/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3RoZS0xay1jaGFsbGVuZ2U_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWpveSUyMHJlbWluZGVyJTIwMjEwNzI1JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXM=
) and, as much as you try to prepare for these things, there‚Äôs
always a few last minute curve balls (like the website
unexpectedly crashing üò¨) that we need to deal with üòÖ

In theory, everything should be back to normal now so if you are
interested in the idea of financial freedom and looking for a
roadmap to get started on that journey, you can find out more
about the Challenge here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/n4u4z20wxvavhxn3vx8a6h6pq0kggalhgvoew/wnhgv6l6f6uq3lq630bl/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3RoZS0xay1jaGFsbGVuZ2U_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWpveSUyMHJlbWluZGVyJTIwMjEwNzI1JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXM=
).

Anyway, on with today‚Äôs email and it actually sort of relates to
The $1k Challenge, or more specifically, the work I‚Äôve been doing
around it because I wanted to talk about the concept of joy as it
relates to productivity. Let me explain.

If you‚Äôve been reading LifeNotes recently or watching some of the
Reels on my Instagram, you might‚Äôve noticed my recent obsession
with Harry Potter fan fiction. Now, before you close the email,
don‚Äôt worry, I‚Äôm not going to go into detail about why it‚Äôs so
good (again üòÖ), instead I wanted to talk about the impact it‚Äôs
had on my productivity.

Over the past few weeks, I‚Äôve been deep in the weeds with The $1k
Challenge - refining modules, tweaking content, wrestling with
technical setups - the kind of work that requires periods of deep
work and focus. Work which can be draining too. And yet I‚Äôve
found myself approaching these tasks with more energy and
creative spark than I‚Äôve felt in months because I‚Äôve been
interspersing these periods of deep work with sessions on the
next novel.

And the thing is, it sort of happened by accident. I didn‚Äôt go
into the first fan fiction book I read thinking that this was
going to be a catalyst for my productivity - if anything, I went
into it a bit sceptical that it‚Äôd be any good (I was wrong). But
the result of getting so engrossed in these books has not just
been an increase in my sense of joy that the stories bring
themselves, but an energy that‚Äôs diffused into every other area
of my life, including my personal productivity.

And this isn‚Äôt surprising - after all, it‚Äôs the idea that sits at
the heart of my book, Feel-Good Productivity - the concept that
feeling good really can drive performance and productivity. But
the thing that‚Äôs surprised me over recent weeks is that sometimes
those energisers, those catalysts for productivity, are not
always obvious or can‚Äôt always be created.

Of course, there are things that we know will give us energy -
exercise, good sleep, meaningful work. But sometimes it‚Äôs the
completely unexpected things that end up being the secret sauce.

For me, it was diving into this completely new world of Harry
Potter fan fiction. For you, it might be learning a random skill
or rediscovering an old hobby. The point is, we often dismiss
these things as ‚Äúdistractions‚Äù when they might actually be
exactly what we need to reignite our drive to take action and
move towards our goals.

And there‚Äôs also something powerful about giving ourselves
permission to be genuinely interested in things without
immediately asking ‚Äúbut how does this help my career?‚Äù or ‚Äúis
this the best use of my time?‚Äù. Sometimes the best use of our
time is following threads of curiosity that make us feel alive
again.

The tricky part is learning to recognise these potential
catalysts and not immediately shutting them down with our inner
critic - and that‚Äôs not easy to do. I‚Äôll be honest, it took a
while for me to connect the dots with these books but I‚Äôll
certainly be more conscious of these opportunities moving
forward. It‚Äôs also made me reflect on a couple of questions that
you might find helpful too this week:

* What would you explore if you gave yourself permission to
follow your curiosity without worrying about whether it‚Äôs
‚Äúproductive‚Äù?
* If you gave yourself permission to spend an hour this week on
something purely because it brings you joy, what would it be?

The bottom line is that sometimes the best productivity hack is
simply allowing yourself to feel genuinely excited about
something, even if it seems completely unrelated to your goals.
Those unexpected bursts of joy and energy have a way of spilling
over into everything else we do.

I hope this was useful - I can‚Äôt promise I won‚Äôt mention Harry
Potter fan fiction again in a newsletter, but I‚Äôll try to hold
off for at least a couple of weeks üòÖ

Finally, just a reminder, The $1k Challenge (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/n4u4z20wxvavhxn3vx8a6h6pq0kggalhgvoew/l2hr93vqf6ulzdl7zxbg/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3RoZS0xay1jaGFsbGVuZ2U_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWpveSUyMHJlbWluZGVyJTIwMjEwNzI1JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXM=

column7: Bridging the Gap: A Data Leader‚Äôs Guide To Helping Your Data Team Create Next Level Analysis
column9:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/bridging-the-gap-a-data-leaders-guide

One of the biggest challenges data leaders have mentioned to me over the past couple of weeks? 
Getting quality work from their analysts.
It‚Äôs not that the analysts are bad at their jobs‚Äîfar from it. But too often, their work gets handed off to stakeholders before it‚Äôs truly ready.
Maybe it‚Äôs missing a clear story. Maybe it doesn‚Äôt drive action. Maybe it‚Äôs overly detailed without getting to the point. Or worse, maybe the numbers aren‚Äôt even accurate.
And honestly? I get it.
After hours spent analyzing data and writing queries, the last thing you want to do is take another hour to refine the narrative and make it compelling enough that stakeholders do more than just stare blankly. But that final step is what separates work that gets ignored from work that drives real change.
So, how can you get more from your team? Let‚Äôs break it down.
1) Make It Clear What ‚ÄúGood‚Äù Looks Like
Most people coming out of college aren‚Äôt trained to deliver an analysis for executives, create a compelling story, and provide actionable results. 
At least, none of my courses covered that. Maybe you did a few case studies, but those didn‚Äôt require you to pull together multiple disparate data sources, query everything, and then make sense of it.
And in school, there were usually right answers.
In the real world? Not so much. And to make things even trickier, no one hands you a guidebook on what a ‚Äúgood‚Äù analysis looks like. You‚Äôre just supposed to figure it out.
Some companies invest heavily in training new hires [ https://substack.com/redirect/e75322b2-1c05-41ec-8167-f2829aa34f66?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]‚Äîand honestly, more should. You do need to set the standard. Yes, analysts need to handle ambiguity, but even if a junior or mid-level analyst had 10 extra hours to polish an analysis, it wouldn‚Äôt necessarily make it better.
Why? Because they don‚Äôt know what they‚Äôre aiming for.
So, show them.
Define what good looks like. Give clear examples. Teach basic techniques. It doesn‚Äôt have to be complicated‚Äîsometimes, simple visual comparisons work best:
If you‚Äôre looking for a good book to buy your analysts(unless they already have it), Story Telling With Data [ https://substack.com/redirect/de2ca86f-8232-4814-9ff6-ae758b0ef350?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] is a classic. The picture above is from their blog and it helps highlight a lot of what I‚Äôve talked about over the past few articles.
Don‚Äôt bury the lede [ https://substack.com/redirect/2fc14979-d0b1-4005-8394-8f8b454c9db7?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] - If there is a take away from a chart, make it clear which they do
Provide support after the main point, notice the ‚Äúbecause of reasons x,y,z‚Äù. You want to have support for your conclusion but you don‚Äôt want to bury it behind a bunch of other facts.
To be clear, you‚Äôre not trying to hamper their own creativity. You want to hire smart people that can solve problems, but that doesn‚Äôt mean you can‚Äôt provide frameworks and guidelines to help them better present their ideas.
A few common challenges analysts run into:
They want to show all their work, so they include four charts when one would do.
They focus too much on how they got to the answer instead of why the answer matters.
They overlook small but critical formatting details‚Äîlike bolding key insights or using color effectively.
These might seem minor, but they make a huge difference in how an analysis is received. And most analysts, myself included, take forever to learn some of these things on their own.
So, don‚Äôt make them figure it out the hard way. Show them what works.
SeattleDataGuy‚Äôs Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
2) Peer Reviews
It‚Äôs interesting‚Äîsoftware engineers regularly review each other‚Äôs code, but I‚Äôve rarely seen analysts review each other‚Äôs analysis or queries. Instead, they often write up their findings, skip the review process, and hand them off as fact. No second set of eyes. No formal data quality checks [ https://substack.com/redirect/7c6cf318-ab68-4c42-a27c-a1677cdd6ff9?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
Now, I get it. You can‚Äôt always implement a lengthy peer review process for every ad-hoc request. But you can put a few simple safeguards in place:
Have analysts write basic data quality check scripts on their own work (though ideally, someone else should verify them).
Implement peer reviews by senior analysts [ https://substack.com/redirect/ece97ee0-6c70-4b15-a9ad-31132d69545a?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] to ensure:
A clear and structured story
Well-formed, actionable insights
A quick sniff test on the numbers
Does this take extra time? Yes.
But let‚Äôs be honest‚Äîwe all put in a little more effort when we know someone‚Äôs watching and likely to critique our work. If I‚Äôm at the gym and someone asks to work-in on my set, you better believe I‚Äôm adding extra weight and pushing myself more.
The same goes for analysis. A second review makes everyone more accountable‚Äîand leads to stronger, more reliable insights.
3) Teach People the Power of Story
Analytics deliverables come in many forms, but whether you‚Äôre building a dashboard, writing a report, or giving a presentation, the goal is the same‚Äîyou need to tell a story with your data.
You could take the easy route and simply present some numbers. Or, you could guide your audience through a narrative that helps them understand why the data matters and what they should do with it.
To craft a strong story [ https://substack.com/redirect/95b66622-fb13-4b7e-913a-9d2bf8d3935e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], you should be able to answer the following:
Who is your audience?
What does your audience care about(what pain points do they feel)?
How do you want your audience to feel after seeing your presentation?
What actions do you want them to take?
In fact, I just heard Mark Freeman  say something similar on Joe Reis ‚Äôs podcast when they were talking about creating content. 
At the end of the day, you can be just another analyst handing over numbers, or you can be the one who drives real decisions and change.
Tactical Tips
Before wrapping up, let‚Äôs go over some tactical tips you can apply‚Äîwhether you‚Äôre a data leader or an individual contributor.
Create a Framework for Analysis: When I did my first analysis, I was all over the place‚Äîtoo many thoughts, a lot of questions, and no clear direction. That‚Äôs the nature of analysis: you can always dig deeper. Without structure, it‚Äôs easy to get lost. Help your team by creating a framework that acts as a guide. It doesn‚Äôt need to be rigid, but it should provide clear steps analysts can follow to organize their work, focus on key insights, and deliver results efficiently.
Onboarding [ https://substack.com/redirect/e75322b2-1c05-41ec-8167-f2829aa34f66?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] Matters: When I spoke with Joe Reis and Richard Millington, both mentioned the importance of onboarding. They created materials to help consultants understand expectations from day one. Why? Because their reputation‚Äîand their business‚Äîdepends on quality work. The same applies to data leaders. If you want consistent, high-quality analysis, take the time to set expectations upfront. A strong onboarding program ensures new hires understand what‚Äôs expected and reduces the trial-and-error phase.
Provide an Example of a Good Analysis: Once someone broke the four-minute mile, others quickly followed (ok, not everyone‚ÄîI‚Äôm definitely not close). The point is that when people know what‚Äôs possible, they know what to aim for. If you have an example of a well-done analysis‚Äîwhether from a past employee or your own work‚Äîkeep it. Use it as a benchmark during onboarding. Break down why it‚Äôs effective so others can learn from it.
Some risks come with introducing a framework‚Äîpeople might stick to it too rigidly, which isn‚Äôt ideal. While structure is helpful, you don‚Äôt want it to stifle critical thinking. Encourage your team to go beyond the basics but still hold them to a standard.
Perhaps it‚Äôs the side of me that started my career in fine-dining, but someone has to call you out when you‚Äôre putting out bad or mediocre work.
In the famous words of a sous-chef I once worked for:
‚ÄúIf you‚Äôre ok with mediocrity, then I guess so am I.‚Äù
Final Thoughts
Many analysts never had anyone show them what a good analysis looks like. No one taught them how to write effective recommendations or highlight key points.
Maybe they were lucky, and they had a professor with business experience who at least emphasized getting to the point quickly. Maybe they didn‚Äôt. But if you want to get more from your data team [ https://substack.com/redirect/1a7a5603-987b-449c-af04-a5dc54b6761c?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], you need to put in the effort to set clear standards.
If you have an analysis that stood out or a strong example to reference, use it. Consider creating a guidebook on how to write and present metrics and outcomes effectively. Books and resources can help, but having a solid internal example is always a great place to start.
As always, thanks for reading.

Bring Instant Clarity to Business Objectives
By Ergest Xheblati [ https://substack.com/redirect/278fdae8-f647-4b4f-aa5f-a4756f7f01cd?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Before I got into data engineering I tried my hand at data analysis. I hated it.
I just couldn‚Äôt figure out what people wanted out of data. Whatever questions I could answer led to more questions and whatever features I could add to a dashboard led to even more feature requests.
It was incredibly frustrating.
Even when I asked people what they wanted, gathered data requirements, built and released multiple reports and dashboards it never seemed to satisfy. On top of that, the dashboards wouldn‚Äôt even be used.
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/c3340647-6116-48e4-b505-2394de41b06f?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
How To Data Model ‚Äì Real Life Examples Of How Companies Model Their Data
How companies data model varies widely.
They might say they use Kimball dimensional modeling. However, when you look in their data warehouse the only part you recognize is the word fact and dim.
Over the past near decade, I have worked for and with different companies that have used various methods to capture this data. I wanted to review some of the techniques that are commonly used to model data for analytics.
This is part of my unofficial series on data modeling, so if you‚Äôd like to learn more, then you can check out some of the prior articles such as this one [ https://substack.com/redirect/df02ae1f-7049-4132-8e2c-01e68686d311?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
But for now, let‚Äôs dive in.

column8: Free Big SQL Energy Beginner Course Lesson 4
column10:
View this post on the web at https://jessramosdata.substack.com/p/free-big-sql-energy-beginner-course-84f

Got BDE?‚ö°Ô∏è
Hi BDEs! Welcome to Lesson 4 of the free Big SQL Energy Beginner Course‚ö°Ô∏è Today we‚Äôre learning how to limit datasets with LIMIT and TOP!
If you‚Äôre new here, I‚Äôm Jess Ramos, the founder of Big Data Energy and the creator of the BEST SQL course and community: Big SQL Energy‚ö°Ô∏è. Check me out on socials: üîóLinkedIn [ https://substack.com/redirect/fde10bfb-ca23-4799-8532-ccdfbaaec712?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], üîóInstagram [ https://substack.com/redirect/ab413d79-4aeb-41cd-9bf4-a91209d1118c?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], üîóYouTube [ https://substack.com/redirect/c567192f-8c15-4c02-bc93-a01aeacb095d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], and üîóTikTok [ https://substack.com/redirect/39f704b4-d7cc-4e76-a314-92c5e37e780b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
Big SQL Energy Intermediate is an intermediate SQL course designed to solve real business problems hands-on using realistic data and a modern tech stack. You‚Äôll walk away with 2 SQL portfolio projects, portfolio building guidance, access to the Big Data Energy Discord community, and lots of confidence for you upcoming coding interviews. This course is all of the most important things I‚Äôve learned on the job as a Senior Data Analyst in tech who grew from a $72K salary to over $150K salary. And now I‚Äôm sharing it with YOU!
                                  Use code Jan2025 for 20% off for all of January!
But if you‚Äôre here for the free BEGINNER Big SQL Energy course, the next lesson for you is below! ‚¨áÔ∏è
Lesson 0: Intro & Getting Started
üé• Video [ https://substack.com/redirect/4d224872-809d-4650-bbce-c2fb7822433b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Before you start, you‚Äôll need access to any IDE (integrated development environment) for SQL of your choosing. I highly recommend using a üîóHex data science notebook [ https://substack.com/redirect/018536c0-7958-4bd6-9a69-5f0ceec8f5ac?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] because it‚Äôs easy to get started with and stored in the cloud‚Äî so no headaches to download and set up. However, you can alternatively use DBeaver, MySQL Workbench, SSMS, or any others if you‚Äôd prefer. Just import the dataset used in the lesson, and you‚Äôre ready to go! Remember, if you get stuck or experience errors, ChatGPT and Gemini are great resources to learn about syntax and help you debug. Alright, let‚Äôs get started!
üîó Join Hex Data Science Notebooks: https://app.hex.tech/signup/big-data-energy [ https://substack.com/redirect/018536c0-7958-4bd6-9a69-5f0ceec8f5ac?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
üîó Datasets (Orders & Customers): https://github.com/jessramosdata/big-sql-energy-beginner [ https://substack.com/redirect/2eb475dc-170a-4256-b87d-da7cbd37e454?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Lesson 4: Limit & Top
üé• Video [ https://substack.com/redirect/5c931718-284b-4d2d-80ce-76e1dc5057e5?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Very often when working with data, we‚Äôre working with A LOT of data. In a course or sandbox environment, you‚Äôre likely only working with a few rows, or hundreds if you‚Äôre lucky! In the real world, tables will have millions of rows which can take a long time to process‚Ä¶ and be very expensive! Many of the new cloud platforms (like Snowflake and other data warehouses) bill based on usage (either on the amount of data pulled or computation time), so it‚Äôs essential as a data analyst to work as efficiently as possible. Not only do you not want to wait 20 minutes for your query to load, but it‚Äôll likely be more expensive for your company.
Of course I have a ton of tips for query optimization when writing queries in my üîóintermediate course [ https://substack.com/redirect/fde7ebac-d02b-4cd8-ac39-398508eec18b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], but I‚Äôm going to show you a quick tip that is great for beginners. Let‚Äôs start with:
select 
   * 
from 
   orders
Based on what I told you about there being lots of data in the real world and the cost of computing data, what do you think about this query? What would it look like in the real world, and are there any issues you can think of? If you‚Äôre thinking that pulling in ALL the columns and ALL the rows from a table is probably not a great idea, YOU ARE RIGHT!
So yes, a great start would be to list the actual columns we need instead of just using *. You might not see a huge need in this dataset, but I‚Äôve seen tables in the real world from CRMs (like HubSpot and Salesforce) with HUNDREDs of columns, so be specific instead of being lazy with * can make a big difference there. 
The main focus of this lesson will actually be about LIMIT. Limit is the method we can use to reduce the rows of our output and get a sneak peek of our data which is a lot more optimized than pulling in the entire table. (Note that limit is at the very end of the order of execution, so it‚Äôs good to think about optimization higher up in the order of execution as well. I talk a lot more about this in my üîóintermediate course [ https://substack.com/redirect/fde7ebac-d02b-4cd8-ac39-398508eec18b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], but don‚Äôt worry too much about this now if you‚Äôre a beginner.) You can add LIMIT to the end of any query and follow with how many rows you want in the output:
select 
   * 
from 
   orders 
limit 
   10; 

select 
   *
from 
   orders 
limit 
   100; 

select 
   *
from 
   orders 
limit 
   1000; 

select 
   *
from 
   orders 
limit 
   678; 
Sometimes a quick 10 rows is enough to see a brief sample of your data, but other times you might need a larger sample to see more values so 100 or 1000 rows is better suited. I know 1000 seems like a lot of rows, but remember tables in the real world have MILLIONS!
Note that LIMIT is not supported in all SQL dialects and platforms, but it is supported in most of the newer ones. If it‚Äôs not working in the IDE you‚Äôre working in, check out TOP. You can always ChatGPT the syntax for limiting rows in the platform you‚Äôre working in if you have trouble!
Now that we‚Äôve learned some super basics, we‚Äôre going to head into a bunch of functions and operations in the next few lessons!
If you‚Äôve enjoyed the free BEGINNER Big SQL Energy course, grab my intermediate course for 20% off NOW because this deal expires February 1. There are no deadlines or timelines for this course‚Äî you start and take as long as you want. It will take your beginner skills to the next level and get you ready to ace your interviews.
DM me or email me at courses@bdeanalytics.com if you have questions on the intermediate course!
-xoxo,
jessüíï
WHO AM I?‚ö°Ô∏è
I'm Jess Ramos, a content creator, instructor, and leader in the data world. I'm super passionate about data and especially SQL‚Äî which inspired me to launch my own SQL course, Big SQL Energy! My 9-5 is being a Senior Data Analyst in tech. I'm also an Instructor with LinkedIn Learning and the founder of Big Data Energy Analytics. My 5-9 (aka outside of my regular job!) is creating amazing content for YOU on LinkedIn [ https://substack.com/redirect/fde10bfb-ca23-4799-8532-ccdfbaaec712?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], Instagram [ https://substack.com/redirect/bd0f7f7c-450e-4193-bf12-c26ebe453529?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], TikTok [ https://substack.com/redirect/39f704b4-d7cc-4e76-a314-92c5e37e780b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]-- and this newsletter!ü§©
Big Data Energy‚ö°Ô∏è is a MUST subscribe if you want BDE in your data career.

***********************
Hey there, Ghostwriter!
***********************

Welcome to the Premium Ghostwriting Blueprint‚Äîwhere every week we
help you knock down high-ticket clients as a Premium Ghostwriter
(even if you‚Äôre a full-time Freelance Writer, or you have a 9-5).

As a reminder: If you'd like to accelerate your trajectory as a
Premium Ghostwriter, don't forget to subscribe to my YouTube
channel (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/75uo4eeqwos2u2m997hzhw6mv966tn/7qh7h2uo33z2wxf9/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vQG5pY29sYXNjb2xlNzc=
). Every week, I share new videos breaking down the skills,
frameworks, & strategies you need to build a profitable writing
business with 26,000+ others.

Today we want to help you price your ghostwriting service (and
start increasing your income).
-----------------------------------------------------------------

Congratulations!

The client said YES.

‚ÄúBut how much should I charge?!‚Äù

Great question‚Äîlet‚Äôs talk money.

****************************************************
How To Think About Pricing Your Ghostwriting Service
****************************************************

There are 5 levels to increasing your income as a ghostwriter.

* Charging per word
* Charging per hour
* Charging per month
* Charging per asset
* Charging per outcome

Let‚Äôs take a brief look at each one and where you should be
thinking about positioning yourself as a Premium Ghostwriter.

Level 1: Charging Per Word
--------------------------

You want to escape this level as quickly as you can.

The fact that your value is tied to the number of words you write
means you inherently have very little long-term pricing power.

Move on.

Level 2: Charging Per Hour
--------------------------

Getting paid per hour is a simple way to be compensated‚Äîin the
beginning.

But you do NOT want to be in the business of your value being
tied to ‚Äúeffort‚Äù for long. There is no incentive to get better or
get your work done faster.

Why would you if it means you actually make less money?

Level 3: Charging Per Month
---------------------------

Is this better than being paid per word? Yes.

Is this better than being paid per hour? Usually. But getting
paid in exchange to do ‚Äúanything‚Äù the client needs is a giant
mistake‚Äîand almost always ends up earning you less than if you
had just charged hourly.

Make sure you are very specific about what you will and won‚Äôt do.

Level 4: Charging Per Asset
---------------------------

This is the correct, and most lucrative, way to monetize your
skills as a ghostwriter.

All the client cares about is whether or not you successfully did
what you said you were going to do. You create an asset (like a
5-Day Educational Email Course), and you charge a fee for the
creation of that asset.

The measure for success has nothing to do with a) your time, or
b) your effort.

Level 5: Charging Per Outcome
-----------------------------

This is the ultimate goal, and where you end up making the most
money as a ghostwriter (or Solopreneur of any kind).

The only way to increase your pricing power above Level 4 is to
share in the OUTCOME you generate. Either you participate in some
sort of profit-sharing model, or you own some equity in the
business you are helping to accelerate.

Both of these vehicles are rare, and likely not something you‚Äôre
going to unlock in the early stages of your career.

*****************************************************************
Accelerate yourself to Level 4 as quickly as possible (and
optimize for several years).
*****************************************************************

Raise your prices.

Build efficiencies.

Once you‚Äôve pushed Level 4 as far as you can, start looking for
specific, advantageous opportunities to reach up to Level 5 and
elevate yourself further by being rewarded for the outcome you
successfully generate for yourself and whomever you partner with.

Now that you know how to think about pricing, it‚Äôs time to name
your price.

**************************************
How To Price Your Ghostwriting Service
**************************************

‚Äã
To make sure you aren‚Äôt undercharging or overcharging relative to
general expectations, here are are the going rates (in a range)
of the most-popular ghostwritten services.

Ghostwriting Social Media Accounts (Twitter, LinkedIn, etc.)

* Low-end: $1,500 per month for 1-2 Tweets per day and 1 Thread
per week.
* High-end: $10,000+ per month for 2-4 Tweets per day and 2-3
Threads per week.
‚Äã

Ghostwriting Thought Leadership Articles

* Low-end: $300 per 800-word article.
* High-end: $5,000+ per 800-word article.
‚Äã

Ghostwriting Keynote Speeches

* Low-end: $3,000 per speech.
* High-end: $20,000+ per speech.
‚Äã

Ghostwriting Startup Pitches & Pitch Decks

* Low-end: $2,000 per pitch deck.
* High-end: $10,000+ per pitch deck.
‚Äã

Ghostwriting Educational Email Courses

* Low-end: $1,000 per email course.
* High-end: $5,000+ per email course.
‚Äã

Ghostwriting Landing Pages

* Low-end: $1,500 per landing page.
* High-end: $10,000+ per landing page.
‚Äã
* Ghostwriting Video Scripts* Low-end: $200 per video.
* High-end: $2,000 per video.

Ghostwriting Books & eBooks

* Low-end: $10,000 per book.
* High-end: $250,000 per book.

There are outliers for all of these‚ÄîUpwork freelancers who charge
significantly less, and celebrity writers who charge tremendously
more.

Find your service.

Name your price.

That‚Äôs it!

Got BDE?‚ö°Ô∏è
Hi BDEs! Welcome to Lesson 5 of the free Big SQL Energy Beginner Course‚ö°Ô∏è Today we‚Äôre learning how to check the data type of a column and convert data types with CAST!
If you‚Äôre enjoying this course, share on social media and tag me and lmk what you think so far! I want to hear from YOU! ‚ù§Ô∏è
If you‚Äôre new here, I‚Äôm Jess Ramos, the founder of Big Data Energy and the creator of the BEST SQL course and community: Big SQL Energy‚ö°Ô∏è. Check me out on socials: üîóLinkedIn [ https://substack.com/redirect/a86e3cbe-3c52-4fd2-a5ad-0f087c6d8aeb?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], üîóInstagram [ https://substack.com/redirect/8684f9b9-91dd-4bbf-859d-ac512d9507d3?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], üîóYouTube [ https://substack.com/redirect/aa304626-2e79-4459-8d34-eadb529742e7?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], and üîóTikTok [ https://substack.com/redirect/f1b75d2b-621f-40fe-8ab2-ae024522de01?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
Big SQL Energy Intermediate is an intermediate SQL course designed to solve real business problems hands-on using realistic data and a modern tech stack. You‚Äôll walk away with 2 SQL portfolio projects, portfolio building guidance, access to the Big Data Energy Discord community, and lots of confidence for you upcoming coding interviews. This course is all of the most important things I‚Äôve learned on the job as a Senior Data Analyst in tech who grew from a $72K salary to over a $150K salary. And now I‚Äôm sharing it with YOU!
                                  Use code Jan2025 for 20% off for all of January!
But if you‚Äôre here for the free BEGINNER Big SQL Energy course, the next lesson for you is below! ‚¨áÔ∏è
Lesson 0: Intro & Getting Started
üé• Video [ https://substack.com/redirect/1e9ac445-094e-43cc-91a7-9d6abe4b1e27?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Before you start, you‚Äôll need access to any IDE (integrated development environment) for SQL of your choosing. I highly recommend using a üîóHex data science notebook [ https://substack.com/redirect/fc141397-1f24-4a6e-b34a-e58ab96e7873?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] because it‚Äôs easy to get started with and stored in the cloud‚Äî so no headaches to download and set up. However, you can alternatively use DBeaver, MySQL Workbench, SSMS, or any others if you‚Äôd prefer. Just import the dataset used in the lesson, and you‚Äôre ready to go! Remember, if you get stuck or experience errors, ChatGPT and Gemini are great resources to learn about syntax and help you debug. Alright, let‚Äôs get started!
üîó Join Hex Data Science Notebooks: https://app.hex.tech/signup/big-data-energy [ https://substack.com/redirect/fc141397-1f24-4a6e-b34a-e58ab96e7873?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
üîó Datasets (Orders & Customers): https://github.com/jessramosdata/big-sql-energy-beginner [ https://substack.com/redirect/de131ab6-cd79-464f-8198-08b9ac62ef67?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Lesson 5: Data Types & Cast
üé• Video [ https://substack.com/redirect/f4408c69-654c-4e02-8b09-89885dc74981?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Think about all the different kinds of data that exists out there‚Ä¶
A list of customers with their names, address, and phone numbers. 
A chart of patients with all their health data like weight, height, and age. 
Stock data with prices for every date this year. 
There‚Äôs a huge variety of data in the real world that results in different formats in the database. Some of the main ones are:
String / Varchar: text data like a name, address, or customer feedback text box
Integers: whole numbers without decimal places like age, number of people, or subscription count (you can‚Äôt have 1.35 people or 67.98 subscriptions!)
Decimals: numbers with decimal places like price, revenue, or rainfall amount
Dates: Date values without a timestamp like 2024-01-03
Datetimes: Date values with a timestamp like 2024-01-03 03:09:26
Many of these data types have additional formatting options that are optional where you can specify the date format, max characters in a string, and even the number of decimal places to keep in a decimal number. For these, I just Google as I need them! All you have to do is figure out the correct format for what you‚Äôre looking for, do a few tests in SQL, and QA to make sure you really did what you meant to.
There are also a bunch of subcategories for data types as well that can be even more niche and specific, but you really don‚Äôt need to know all of them. If you ever have a use case for them, you can just do a quick google or ChatGPT to figure out which one you need. I promise you don‚Äôt need to memorize ALL the different formats. Just understand what they mean and be ready to google, apply, and test (QA) as needed! Being a good data analyst (especially senior!) is being able to figure things out and apply examples to your scenario.
Now that we have an understanding of the different data types we might experience in a database, let‚Äôs talk about some real stuff for a second. Have you ever heard of data cleaning? Chances are, you‚Äôve heard jokes about it because it‚Äôs a huge part of a data analyst‚Äôs job (and a huge pain in the B.U.T.T.), but you might not know what it is. One common issue in a database is that data can be imported or loaded into a database in incorrect formats (or maybe the data was just incorrect in the first place at the source). For example, a date might be showing up as a string, an integer might be showing up as a decimal, or a string might be showing up as an integer.
Why does this matter? Well sometimes we need to clean up field so they look better and more appropriate in the output, but more commonly, we need to convert datatypes in order to use them in relevant functions. For example, only dates can be used in date functions, so if your data imported as text, you might be out of luck using that date function. (You‚Äôll get an error about an incorrect data type and need to convert it to fix it and use it in the function. This caused me MANY headaches as a new data analyst, so let‚Äôs learn how to fix it!).
(BTW if you‚Äôre new to functions in SQL, functions basically mean you put something IN and get something OUT. You put in values or columns (called inputs or arguments) and you get out some sort of output based on what the function does)
We can use the CAST() function to convert values & fields between data types. Here‚Äôs some examples below:
select 
   cast(order_date, varchar),    --converts date to string/varchar
   cast(coupon, integer),        --converts decimal to integer
   cast(order_date, datetime),   --converts date to datetime
   cast(price, decimal)          --converts integer to decimal
from 
   orders;
***Note the CAST function syntax may differ slightly between dialects and platforms. ChatGPT if needed!
Here‚Äôs a secret insider secret if you don‚Äôt wanna look like a newbie:
A lot of newer cloud platforms (like Snowflake) support a shorthand notion of CAST with 2 colons (::) after the value or column name.
select 
   order_date::varchar), 
   coupon::integer, 
   order_date::datetime, 
   price::decimal 
from 
   orders;
Changing the data type of a column in a query doesn‚Äôt change the data type in the original source table, only creates that new version temporarily in your query. Now that we know how to convert data types in SQL, let‚Äôs move onto some other FUN functions and operations!
If you‚Äôve enjoyed the free BEGINNER Big SQL Energy course, grab my intermediate course for 20% off NOW because this deal expires February 1. There are no deadlines or timelines for this course‚Äî you start and take as long as you want. It will take your beginner skills to the next level and get you ready to ace your interviews.
DM me or email me at courses@bdeanalytics.com if you have questions on the intermediate course!
-xoxo,

We just rolled out Visily 4.2‚Äîand it‚Äôs packed with updates designed to make your workflows faster, AI editing more reliable, and team collaboration smoother.

There‚Äôs a lot to love in this release. Let‚Äôs get into it ‚Üì

Improved Browser Extension

When browsing sites with sample UI examples, simply hover over a UI template image to capture it instantly. It saves directly to your Visily account, and you can select only the images you want to import‚Äîleaving the clutter behind.

See the extension update ‚Üí ( https://www.visily.ai/release-notes/release-note-v4-2-oct-2025/?utm_source=custio&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=release-note&utm_content=V4.2&utm_term=screenshot-extension-update#screenshot-extension-update )

AI fill for text components¬†

Need placeholder text that's actually good? You can now ask the AI to fill in text for things like buttons, tables, and input fields based on the structure. You get smarter, useful content instantly, instead of random filler.

Try text fill ‚Üí ( https://app.visily.ai/try/fill_content_with_ai?utm_source=custio&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=release-note&utm_content=V4.2&utm_term=ai-content-filler )

Interactive drop down

With the new interactive dropdown, you can create dropdowns that work in prototype mode, responding to clicks for a more realistic, high-fidelity experience in presentations and user tests.

Give it a try ‚Üí ( https://app.visily.ai/try/interactive_dropdown?utm_source=custio&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=release-note&utm_content=V4.2&utm_term=interactive-dropdown )
